<paper id="1571104860"><title>On the Selection of Pairing-Friendly Groups</title><year>2003</year><authors><author org="Universidade de Sao Paulo#TAB#" id="2092095195">Paulo S. L. M. Barreto</author><author org="Stanford, University" id="2159437062">Ben Lynn</author><author org="Dublin City University, Ballymun" id="2585147799">Michael Scott</author></authors><n_citation>161</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1509042961</reference><reference>1513535488</reference><reference>1518871948</reference><reference>1537065876</reference><reference>1602301309</reference><reference>1610688607</reference><reference>2060770809</reference><reference>2071680489</reference><reference>2086042811</reference><reference>2091260227</reference><reference>2487059806</reference><reference>2566289402</reference></references><venue id="2758123139" type="C">Selected Areas in Cryptography</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-24654-1_2</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.50367">Embedding</keyword><keyword weight="0.50118">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.45614">Arithmetic</keyword><keyword weight="0.63386">Pairing</keyword><keyword weight="0.47673">Cryptosystem</keyword><keyword weight="0.67622">Tate pairing</keyword><keyword weight="0.45709">Bandwidth (signal processing)</keyword><keyword weight="0.4768">SIMPLE algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.41184">Mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.47107">Elliptic curve</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We propose a simple algorithm to select group generators suitable for pairing-based cryptosystems. The selected parameters are shown to favor implementations of the Tate pairing that are at once conceptually simple and efficient, with an observed performance about 2 to 10 times better than previously reported implementations, depending on the embedding degree. Our algorithm has beneficial side effects: various non-pairing operations become faster, and bandwidth may be saved.</abstract></paper>